# Import Risk-Free Rate from the treasurey yields
rf_rate = pd.read_csv('/content/gdrive/MyDrive/409 Final Project/1-year-treasury-rate-yield-chart.csv', 
                       index_col = 0, parse_dates = True).ffill()
rf_rate.columns = ['rfr']

### The Risk-Free Rates are an annual rate based on the price 
### of the 1-year Treasure Bond on the given day. So to to get 
### Monthly risk-free rates we need to:
    ## i_m = [(1 + i_a) **(1/12)] - 1
# Note: We want Monthly since our data is monhtly

rf_rate = (((rf_rate / 100) + 1) ** (1/12)) - 1



# Adding the Risk-Free Rate to our DataFrame
data = pd.merge_asof(data, rf_rate, left_index = True, 
                     right_index = True)

## Scale the Data:
    # We want the data to be comparable & on the same scale
def scale(X):
    num = X - X.min()
    denom = X.max() - X.min()
    return num/denom

scaled_data = pd.DataFrame(index = data.index)
scaled_data['US_ir'] = scale(data['United States Interest'])
scaled_data['UK_ir'] = scale(data['United Kingdom Interest'])


scaled_data['US_inf'] = scale(data['United States Inflation'])
scaled_data['UK_inf'] = scale(data['United Kingdom Inflation'])

scaled_data['US_unemp'] = scale(data['United States Unemployment'])
scaled_data['UK_unemp'] = scale(data['United Kingdom Unemployment'])

scaled_data['DEXUSUK'] = data['DEXUSUK']

Outline Trading Rules based on these forecasts:¶

  • Long/short positions
  • exiting positions

Kalman Filter:

  • Hyperparameters:
    • z: standard deviations
    • k: the gain
    • w: number of lags
    • h: holding period

Long Positions: differential falls below the filter plus some number of standard deviations (z)
Short Positions: differential rises above the filter plus some standard deviations (z)

Interest Rate Differential¶

Optimize at least 2 strategy Hyperparameters:¶

  • length of holding period
  • model hyperparameters (alpha for lasso, number of lags to include, rolling window size, etc)

# specify candidate values for hyperparameters
ks = np.linspace(0.1, .99, 10)
zs = np.linspace(0.1, 3, 7)
ws = np.arange(1, 24, 3) 
hs = np.arange(1, 12, 1) ## Because we have monthly data, our holding period is in terms of months 

import itertools as it
# build a grid with all possible hyperparameters
grid = np.array(np.meshgrid(ks,zs,ws,hs)).T.reshape(-1,4)
In [ ]:
storage = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["k", "z", "w", "h", "profits"])

for n in range(len(grid)):
    # Each loop we pull out the values for a new set of hyperparamters from the grid
    k,z,w,h= grid[n]
    
    # We fit a filter and CI using the next set of parameters
    train_diffs["Filter"] = train_diffs["ir_diff"].ewm(alpha = k, adjust = False).mean()
    train_diffs["Filter Error"] = train_diffs["ir_diff"] -train_diffs["Filter"]
    train_diffs["std"] = train_diffs["Filter Error"].rolling(int(w)).std()
    train_diffs["Upper"] = train_diffs["Filter"] + z*train_diffs["std"]
    train_diffs["Lower"] = train_diffs["Filter"] - z*train_diffs["std"]
    train_diffs["test"] = np.where(train_diffs["Filter Error"].abs()>z*train_diffs["std"], 1, 0)*np.sign(train_diffs["Filter Error"])
    
    # create vectors where we can store information on signals and when the change is first signalled
    train_diffs["test2"] = 0
    train_diffs["signal"] = 0
    
    for j in train_diffs.index:
        # if there is a change in the signal, we want to take a position for teh next h periods
        if (train_diffs.loc[j, "test"] == 1) &  (train_diffs.shift().loc[j, "test"] != 1):
            train_diffs.loc[j:j+datetime.timedelta(h), "signal"] = 1
            train_diffs.loc[j, "test2"] = 1
        elif (train_diffs.loc[j, "test"] == -1) &  (train_diffs.shift().loc[j, "test"] != -1):
            train_diffs.loc[j:j+datetime.timedelta(h), "signal"] =  -1
            train_diffs.loc[j, "test2"] = -1
    
# calculate metric
    train_diffs["cumulative_returns"] = (np.exp((train_diffs["signal"].shift()*train_diffs.returns).cumsum())-1)*100

    # store the results
    storage = storage.append({"k":k, "z":z, "w":w, "h":h ,"profits":train_diffs["cumulative_returns"][-1]}, ignore_index = True)
    #print so I can track progress of loop (can take a few minutes)
    #print(n)

# Heatmaps

def heatmap(x, y, metric, values):
    
    # specify the columns I will be pulling from the results
    p2p = values[[x, y, metric]]
    
    # If p > 2, we need to group 
    heat = np.round(p2p.groupby([x,y]).max(),1)
    heat = heat.unstack()[metric]

    # round labels
    heat.index = np.round(heat.index,2)
    heat.columns = np.round(heat.columns,2)

    # make plot
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 8))
    ax = sns.heatmap(heat, fmt='.1g')
    ax.set_title("Heat map of "+ metric,size = 15)
    ax.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=10)
    ax.set_xlabel(y, size = 15)
    ax.set_ylabel(x, size = 15)
    ax.collections[0].colorbar.set_label(metric, size = 15)
    sns.set(font_scale=1)
    plt.show()

## Implementing the Strategy with the Optimal Results 
### Apply the Strategy to the final 20% of the dataset:
ir_strategy = test_diffs.copy()


# Applying the Strategy
ir_strategy["Filter"] = ir_strategy["ir_diff"].ewm(alpha = k, adjust = False).mean()
ir_strategy["Filter Error"] = ir_strategy["ir_diff"] -ir_strategy["Filter"]
ir_strategy["std"] = ir_strategy["Filter Error"].rolling(int(w)).std()
ir_strategy["Upper"] = ir_strategy["Filter"] + z*ir_strategy["std"]
ir_strategy["Lower"] = ir_strategy["Filter"] - z*ir_strategy["std"]

ir_strategy["test"] = np.where(ir_strategy["Filter Error"].abs()>z*ir_strategy["std"], 
                             1, 0)*np.sign(ir_strategy["Filter Error"])

ir_strategy["test2"] = 0
ir_strategy["signal"] = 0
for j in ir_strategy.index:
    if (ir_strategy.loc[j, "test"] == 1)&(ir_strategy.shift().loc[j,"test"] != 1):
        ir_strategy.loc[j:j+datetime.timedelta(h), "signal"] = 1
        ir_strategy.loc[j, "test2"] = 1
    elif (ir_strategy.loc[j, "test"] == -1)&(ir_strategy.shift().loc[j, "test"] != -1):
        ir_strategy.loc[j:j+datetime.timedelta(h), "signal"] =  -1
        ir_strategy.loc[j, "test2"] = -1
        
        
cum_return_exp = (ir_strategy["signal"].shift()*ir_strategy.returns).cumsum()

ir_strategy["cumulative_returns"]=np.exp(cum_return_exp)-1
ir_strategy["strat_returns"] = ir_strategy["signal"].shift()*ir_strategy.returns

## Setting up the Binomial Test
start = daily_strat[['USUK', 'signal']].index[0]

df = daily_strat[daily_strat.test != 0][['signal', 'USUK']].copy()
df = df[:-2]
df['D'] = df['signal']

df['s_current'] = daily_strat[daily_strat.index.isin(df.index)]['USUK'].values
df['s_future'] = daily_strat[daily_strat.index.isin(df.index +
                    datetime.timedelta(i))]['USUK'].values

# Get the realized exchange Rate
df['R'] = np.where(df['s_future'] >= df['s_current'], 1, -1)

# Sample Covariances
df['W'] = (df['D'] - np.mean(df['D']))*(df['R'] - np.mean(df['R']))
T_B = np.mean(df['W'])
In [ ]:
### The Binomial Test

# Calculate LRV estimator
dy = df['W'] - np.mean(df['W'])
gamma_0 = sum((dy)**2)/len(df)
gamma_1 = np.mean((dy*dy.shift(-1))[:len(df) - 1])
LRV = gamma_0 + 2*(1-1/2)*gamma_1

# Creating the Test Statistic & Critical Value
from scipy.stats import norm

statistic = T_B/np.sqrt(LRV/df.shape[0])
cv = round(norm.ppf(0.95), 2)

print('T:', T_B)
print('Test Statistic:', statistic)
print('5% Critical Value:', cv)

T: -0.09485659349463232
Test Statistic: -1.2930617564262326
5% Critical Value: 1.64

### The Weighted Binomial Test
df = df.dropna()

# Weighted Mean
df['W2'] = df['D'] * (df['s_future'] - df['s_current'])
T_WB = np.mean(df['W2'])
print('Weighted T:', T_WB)

# Calculating the LRV Estimator
dy_2 = df['W2'] - np.mean(df['W2'])
gamma_0 = sum((dy_2)**2)/len(df)
gamma_1 = np.mean((dy_2*dy_2.shift(-1))[:len(df) -1])
LRV_2 = gamma_0 + 2*(1-1/2)*gamma_1

# Creating the Test Statistic & Critical Value
statistic_2 = T_WB/np.sqrt(LRV_2/len(df))

print('Test Statistic:', statistic_2)
print('5% Critical Value:', cv)

ks = np.linspace(0.1, .99, 10)

ws = np.arange(1, 24, 3) 
hs = np.arange(1, 12, 1)

# build a grid with all possible hyperparameters
grid = np.array(np.meshgrid(ks,zs,ws,hs)).T.reshape(-1,4)
In [ ]:
storage = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["k", "z", "w", "h", "profits"])

for n in range(len(grid)):
    # Each loop we pull out the values for a new set of hyperparamters from the grid
    k,z,w,h= grid[n]
    
    # We fit a filter and CI using the next set of parameters
    train_diffs["Filter"] = train_diffs["inf_diff"].ewm(alpha = k, adjust = False).mean()
    train_diffs["Filter Error"] = train_diffs["inf_diff"] -train_diffs["Filter"]
    train_diffs["std"] = train_diffs["Filter Error"].rolling(int(w)).std()
    train_diffs["Upper"] = train_diffs["Filter"] + z*train_diffs["std"]
    train_diffs["Lower"] = train_diffs["Filter"] - z*train_diffs["std"]
    train_diffs["test"] = np.where(train_diffs["Filter Error"].abs()>z*train_diffs["std"], 1, 0)\
        *np.sign(train_diffs["Filter Error"])
    
    # create vectors where we can store information on signals and when the change is first signalled
    train_diffs["test2"] = 0
    train_diffs["signal"] = 0
    
    for j in train_diffs.index:
        # if there is a change in the signal, we want to take a position for teh next h periods
        if (train_diffs.loc[j, "test"] == 1) &  (train_diffs.shift().loc[j, "test"] != 1):
            train_diffs.loc[j:j+datetime.timedelta(h), "signal"] = 1
            train_diffs.loc[j, "test2"] = 1
        elif (train_diffs.loc[j, "test"] == -1) &  (train_diffs.shift().loc[j, "test"] != -1):
            train_diffs.loc[j:j+datetime.timedelta(h), "signal"] =  -1
            train_diffs.loc[j, "test2"] = -1
    
# calculate metric
    train_diffs["cumulative_returns"] = (np.exp((train_diffs["signal"].shift()*train_diffs.returns).cumsum())-1)*100

    # store the results
    storage = storage.append({"k":k, "z":z, "w":w, "h":h ,"profits":train_diffs["cumulative_returns"][-1]}, ignore_index = True)
    #print so I can track progress of loop (can take a few minutes)
    #print(n)

storage = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["k", "z", "w", "h", "profits"])

for n in range(len(grid)):
    # Each loop we pull out the values for a new set of hyperparamters from the grid
    k,z,w,h= grid[n]
    
    # We fit a filter and CI using the next set of parameters
    train_diffs["Filter"] = train_diffs["unemp_diff"].ewm(alpha = k, adjust = False).mean()
    train_diffs["Filter Error"] = train_diffs["unemp_diff"] -train_diffs["Filter"]
    train_diffs["std"] = train_diffs["Filter Error"].rolling(int(w)).std()
    train_diffs["Upper"] = train_diffs["Filter"] + z*train_diffs["std"]
    train_diffs["Lower"] = train_diffs["Filter"] - z*train_diffs["std"]
    train_diffs["test"] = np.where(train_diffs["Filter Error"].abs()>z*train_diffs["std"], 1, 0)\
        *np.sign(train_diffs["Filter Error"])
    
    # create vectors where we can store information on signals and when the change is first signalled
    train_diffs["test2"] = 0
    train_diffs["signal"] = 0
    
    for j in train_diffs.index:
        # if there is a change in the signal, we want to take a position for the next h periods
        if (train_diffs.loc[j, "test"] == 1) &  (train_diffs.shift().loc[j, "test"] != 1):
            train_diffs.loc[j:j+datetime.timedelta(h), "signal"] = 1
            train_diffs.loc[j, "test2"] = 1
        elif (train_diffs.loc[j, "test"] == -1) &  (train_diffs.shift().loc[j, "test"] != -1):
            train_diffs.loc[j:j+datetime.timedelta(h), "signal"] =  -1
            train_diffs.loc[j, "test2"] = -1
    
# calculate metric
    train_diffs["cumulative_returns"] = (np.exp((train_diffs["signal"].shift()*train_diffs.returns).cumsum())-1)*100

    # store the results
    storage = storage.append({"k":k, "z":z, "w":w, "h":h ,"profits":train_diffs["cumulative_returns"][-1]}, ignore_index = True)
    #print so I can track progress of loop (can take a few minutes)

# Sharpe Ratio Definition
def sharpe_ratio(returns, rfr):
    excess_returns = returns - rfr
    SR = excess_returns.mean() / excess_returns.std()
    return SR

def highlight_headers(df, header_color):
    # Create a CSS style for the header
    style = '<style>table.dataframe th {{ background-color: {}; color: white; }}</style>'.format(header_color)
